03306nmm a2200529Ia 9780520922389DE-B159720240326120151.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240326t20232000cau    fo  d z      eng d  a97805209223897 a10.1525/97805209223892doi  a(DE-B1597)542760  a(OCoLC)1153459684  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  acaucUS-CA 4aHQ684b.D53 2000 7aHIS0030002bisacsh04a306.85/09512211 aDiamant, Neil J., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aRevolutionizing the Family :bPolitics, Love, and Divorce in Urban and Rural China, 1949–1968 /cNeil J. Diamant.  aReprint 2019 1aBerkeley, CA : bUniversity of California Press, c[2023] 4c©2000  a1 online resource (458 p.) :b4 maps, 3 tables, 2 figs.  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn 1950, China's new Communist government enacted a Marriage Law to allow free choice in marriage and easier access to divorce. Prohibiting arranged marriages, concubinage, and bigamy, it was one of the most dramatic efforts ever by a state to change marital and family relationships. In this comprehensive study of the effects of that law, Neil J. Diamant draws on newly opened urban and rural archival sources to offer a detailed analysis of how the law was interpreted and implemented throughout the country. In sharp contrast to previous studies of the Marriage Law, which have argued that it had little effect in rural areas, Diamant argues that the law reshaped marriage and family relationships in significant--but often unintended--ways throughout the Maoist period. His evidence reveals a confused and often conflicted state apparatus, as well as cases of Chinese men and women taking advantage of the law to justify multiple sexual encounters, to marry for beauty, to demand expensive gifts for engagement, and to divorce on multiple occasions. Moreover, he finds, those who were best placed to use the law's more liberal provisions were not well-educated urbanites but rather illiterate peasant women who had never heard of sexual equality; and it was poor men, not women, who were those most betrayed by the peasant-based revolution.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Mrz 2024) 0aFamiliesxChina. 0aFamilieszChina. 0aFamily policyxChina. 0aFamily policyzChina. 7aHISTORY / Asia / General.2bisacsh40uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/978052092238940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520922389423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520922389/original  aEBA_EMB  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles